task.summary: Default task

- Created a main function to store emails and associated names. - Added input prompts for email and name confirmation. - Included a helper function to extract and format names from email addresses. - Displayed stored emails and names at the end of execution.

- Implemented a dictionary of color names with their corresponding hexadecimal codes. - Created a main function to prompt users for color names and display the associated hex codes. - Included error handling for unrecognized color names. - Allowed users to exit the program by pressing Enter without input.

- Created a dictionary mapping state codes to their full names. - Enabled user input for state codes, allowing case-insensitive entry. - Added validation to check for valid state codes and provide feedback. - Displayed a list of all states and their corresponding names at the end.

- Implemented CSV reading to extract Wimbledon champion data. - Created functions to count wins for each champion and retrieve unique countries. - Displayed sorted lists of champions with their win counts. - Listed unique countries that have won Wimbledon. - Ensured proper handling of CSV file encoding.

- Created a basic Kivy app to demonstrate interactive functionality. - Added buttons dynamically for a list of names and handled their press events. - Implemented a counter with up/down button functionality to update status text. - Utilized Kivy's StringProperty for dynamic updates in the UI. - Set up initial app title and layout using a KV file.

- Defined the layout and widget structure for the Kivy app using KV language. - Configured a vertical BoxLayout containing a Label and two buttons for counter control. - Set up a horizontal BoxLayout for the Up and Down buttons to modify the counter. - Included an id for the names_box to allow dynamic addition of name buttons from the Python code.

- Added a function to count occurrences of each word in a user-provided string. - Utilized a dictionary for counting and sorted the results alphabetically. - Formatted output for aligned display based on the longest word. - Included user input handling and case normalization.

"Added guitars program to store and display guitar details, including vintage check"
"Added languages program to print details and filter dynamically typed languages"
Implemented string representation (`__str__`) for a user-friendly display.

- Refactored CSV reading using the `csv.reader` for better handling of CSV files. - Added error handling for invalid rows (missing or incorrect data). - Skipped rows with missing or malformed data (invalid year format). - Added clearer exception handling for file not found and general errors. - Improved the docstring of the main function for better clarity.

- Added functionality to read and display guitars from a CSV file. - Allowed users to add new guitars interactively and append them to the list. - Implemented sorting of guitars by year and displaying them. - Added saving functionality to store the updated list of guitars back into the CSV file. - Improved code with type annotations for better clarity.

- Created `ProgrammingLanguage` class to represent details about a programming language. - Implemented `__repr__` method for a detailed string representation of the language. - Added `is_dynamic` method to check if the language is dynamically typed. - Added `supports_pointer_arithmetic` method to check if the language supports pointer arithmetic. - Default value for `pointer_arithmetic` is set to `False`

- Created `Project` class to represent project details including name, start date, priority, cost estimate, and completion percentage. - Implemented `__str__` method to return a formatted string representation of the project. - Added `is_completed` method to check if the project is fully completed (100% completion). - Added `compare_by_priority` static method to enable sorting of projects based on priority. - Implemented `update` method to allow updating project completion percentage and priority. - Used `datetime` module to parse and handle project start date.

- Created functions to load projects from a file (`load_projects`) and save them to a file (`save_projects`). - Implemented `display_projects` to show incomplete and completed projects, sorted by priority. - Added filtering functionality (`filter_projects_by_date`) to show projects starting after a specific date. - Implemented `add_new_project` to allow users to input new projects and add them to the list. - Created `update_project` to update a project's completion percentage and/or priority. - Added a simple menu interface with options to load, save, display, filter, add, and update projects. - Supports saving before quitting with the option to select a filename. - Handles file operations and project management tasks iteratively through a user-friendly CLI.
